Hello, sports fans, and welcome back to Wall Power, my
four-times-per-week private email on the inner workings of the art market=
=E2=80=94which includes a bonus Inner Circle issue every Wednesday for hard=
 core professionals, ruthless advisors, billionaire (and aspiring billionai=
re) collectors, and true believers. I=E2=80=99m Marion Maneker.

=C2=A0

Tonight, Julie Davich is going deep on the Saunders collection, which was a=
nnounced late last week by
Sotheby=E2=80=99s. Estimated at $80 million, this will be the most valuable=
 single-owner sale of Old Masters paintings to be offered ever. Sotheby=E2=
=80=99s is sufficiently pumped about this collection to have moved it to Ma=
y, ahead of the normal schedule.

=C2=A0

There=E2=80=99s an added benefit to scheduling the sale then. The preview a=
nd sale will allow collectors of modern and contemporary art=E2=80=94and th=
eir advisors=E2=80=94to see the works when
they are in town. Consider the Saunders sale as lead generation for the Old=
 Masters category. As Julie and I have been telling you, collectors have be=
come interested in Old Masters for the high quality of the art and the lowe=
r prices=E2=80=94in relative terms, of course. Julie gets into all of that =
below.

=C2=A0

But first=E2=80=A6

* A new front in the battle for Artnet: Late last week, as I recounted, Art=
net selected ( https://puck.news/inside-artnets-boardroom-coup/?utm_campaig=
n=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.=
io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) a neutral board of directors at its cont=
entious annual general meeting, but that doesn=E2=80=99t mean the warring f=
actions have made peace. Over the weekend, the company released a statement=
, signed by V.P. Sophie Neuendorf, still obsessing over the company=E2=80=
=99s largest
shareholder, Neuendorf nemesis R=C3=BCdiger Weng=E2=80=94even though by the=
n, Weng had been outmaneuvered by offstage investor Andrew Wolff. =E2=80=9C=
The meeting was at times turbulent,=E2=80=9D the weekend statement reads, =
=E2=80=9Cas one or more shareholders attempted to push their personal inter=
ests with the help of professional disruptors.=E2=80=9D

Presumably, Sophie is referring to the conspiracy theory that Weng had hire=
d a disruptive shareholder to prolong the meeting. Curiously, for what
it=E2=80=99s worth, another neutral attendee ( https://dirkhagemann.substac=
k.com/p/zur-hauptversammlung-der-artnet-ag?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBS=
CRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F=
25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c6061=
7da42abd12a ) speculated that the raucous 14-hour meeting had been staged b=
y the Neuendorfs themselves, in a desperate attempt to stall the proceeding=
s until a white knight emerged in the form of Wolff.

Perhaps not surprisingly, there=E2=80=99s a new showdown brewing, after Wol=
ff seemed to be engineering a takeunder, wherein the
stock price plummets to facilitate a takeover. There=E2=80=99s also been ta=
lk of the company needing to borrow another $1 million from newly elected b=
oard member Roy Israel, just to make payroll in the coming months. Meanwhil=
e, a San Francisco tech turnaround investor named Garry McGuire=E2=80=94who=
 unexpectedly announced at the board meeting that he planned to make a bid=
=E2=80=94has maneuvered himself closer to center stage in the melodramatic =
battle.

Anyway, the Neuendorfs
believe that Weng reneged on a previously agreed-on truce and sabotaged the=
 company=E2=80=99s future by denying them the ability to raise capital. =E2=
=80=9CMr. Weng inexplicably failed to adhere to the agreement on the Superv=
isory Board election,=E2=80=9D the statement continued tartly. =E2=80=9CBy =
doing so, he has once again prioritized his personal interests over those o=
f the company=E2=80=94despite the fact that the art market has been in a se=
vere crisis for years.=E2=80=9D

Who betrayed whom? We=E2=80=99ll probably never know, but the
damage has been done. Artnet=E2=80=99s stock price dropped by as much as 25=
 percent during the four days following the meeting. Meanwhile, Wolff=E2=80=
=99s takeunder plans=E2=80=94which would eventually involve rolling Artnet =
up with other similar digital art businesses=E2=80=94seemed to be proceedin=
g apace until today=E2=80=A6 when Weng announced that he would pledge his 2=
9.5 percent stake in Artnet to Art Technology Holdings, a company McGuire f=
ormed less than a year ago. The partnership would allow McGuire to make his=
 own
bid to acquire Artnet at =E2=82=AC11 a share, which was nearly twice the st=
ock price on Monday. (Artnet shares are now trading in the middle ground of=
 =E2=82=AC7 a share, as investors weigh which way to go.)

Unlike Wolff=E2=80=99s planned roll-up, ATH believes that it can invest up =
to $10 million in the company, install experienced professional management =
instead of family members, and add value across the art market value chain.=
 I haven=E2=80=99t made a secret of my skepticism. Despite its traffic and =
brand, I worry
that there isn=E2=80=99t a large enough addressable market for a revamped a=
nd fully functioning Artnet to grow into the valuation worthy of an acquisi=
tion and subsequent investment. But McGuire is a good tech salesman. Which =
means the battle for Artnet has suddenly shifted: It=E2=80=99s no longer a =
German civil war, but a struggle between Silicon Valley and Wall Street.

Now, let=E2=80=99s get to the main event =E2=80=A6

