Sotheby=E2=80=99s has set its most valuable Old Masters auction ever for Ma=
y: the
Saunders collection, the product of a four-year buying spree fueled by Wall=
 Street money, which could fetch more than $80 million.

Julie Brener Davich ( https://puck.news/author/juliedavich/?utm_campaign=3D=
Wall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Julie Brener Davich ( https://puck.news/author/juliedavich/?utm_campaign=3D=
Wall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

=E2=80=9COld Masters lovers share several traits: curiosity, passion for pr=
ovenance,
love of color and history,=E2=80=9D wrote collector Jordan Saunders, who am=
assed one of the most consequential collections of such paintings in the 20=
th century along with her late husband, the legendary Morgan Stanley banker=
 and private equity O.G. Thomas Saunders III. =E2=80=9CI am in awe of the a=
rtists=E2=80=99 techniques, the stories they tell, all the tiny details, an=
d, in some, the hidden symbolism.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

This May, the Saunders collection will go on sale at Sotheby=E2=80=99s, in =
New York, with an estimate of $80 million=E2=80=94the most valuable single-=
owner compilation ever to hit the block within the category. =E2=80=9CThere=
 are so many high-quality, fabulous-condition pictures in the sale, just on=
e after the other,=E2=80=9D said George Wachter, a Sotheby=E2=80=99s chairm=
an and co-worldwide-head of Old Masters paintings=E2=80=94so many, in fact,=
 that Sotheby=E2=80=99s felt it could sustain a
single-owner event outside the regular Old Masters marquee sale calendar. W=
achter had to alert his clients to add it to their travel schedules. (Discl=
osure: I worked on the Saunders collection proposal when I was at Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s.)

=C2=A0

The timing is fortuitous. May is also when all the modern and contemporary =
collectors are in town, and art advisors have been pitching their clients o=
n the value of Old Masters. Evidence from London
this week=E2=80=94where Sotheby=E2=80=99s displayed highlights from the Sau=
nders collection alongside the presale viewing of modern and contemporary a=
rt=E2=80=94suggests they=E2=80=99re onto something. A Sotheby=E2=80=99s spo=
kesman told me that a well-known contemporary artist happened upon the Saun=
ders trove and =E2=80=9Cgot really jazzed,=E2=80=9D attracting a crowd arou=
nd her as she waxed eloquent about the brushwork.

The Saunders=E2=80=99 New York apartment. Photo: Courtesy of Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s

The couple=E2=80=99s collection spans the 16th to 19th centuries, and repre=
sents some
of the greatest artists of that era, ranging from still lifes by Jan Davids=
z. de Heem and Luis Mel=C3=A9ndez to portraits by Frans Hals and Thomas Law=
rence to vedute by Canaletto and Francesco Guardi, as well as works by Gerr=
it Dou and Peter Paul Rubens. The auction comprises 56 works, with 42 being=
 offered in a dedicated single-owner sale
and the rest in the various-owners sale the following day. By comparison, S=
otheby=E2=80=99s most valuable collection of Old Masters sold to date was t=
he Fisch Davidson collection, which made $76 million in 2023=E2=80=94it was=
 only 12 pictures, all Italian Baroque, with two-thirds of the value coming=
 from just two Rubens paintings.=C2=A0

This will be the first time in decades that the Saunders paintings are comi=
ng on the market, since the couple bought many of them via private
transactions between 1998 and 2002. =E2=80=9CThe Saunderses wanted beautifu=
l pictures in wonderful condition,=E2=80=9D said Wachter, who worked closel=
y with the couple to assemble the collection that would fill their triplex =
penthouse at 812 Park Avenue. =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s amazing is how I mana=
ged to find all these things at that time. Not sure I could do it in the sa=
me way today,=E2=80=9D he told me, in part because Old Masters collections =
like those of Renata and Michal Hornstein,
Rose-Marie and Eijk van Otterloo, and Susan and Matthew Weatherbie have bee=
n donated to museums.

Full Circle
-----------

The Saunders=E2=80=99 collecting journey is ending right where it started. =
In January
1998, Sotheby=E2=80=99s client services executive Mish Tworkowski invited J=
ordan to lunch at the auction house, where they wandered down to the Old Ma=
sters exhibition and happened upon the painting View of the Isola della Giu=
decca, by Guardi. Tworkowski introduced her to Wachter, who spoke eloquentl=
y about the composition. The Saunderses went on to purchase the Guardi at a=
uction for $1.3 million. (It=E2=80=99s being offered in May at an estimate =
of $4 million.) In the same sale, they
underbid a portrait by Johannes Cornelisz Verspronck that ended up being bo=
ught by the National Gallery for $1.65 million.

=C2=A0

Thus began their four-year buying spree and decades-long friendship with Wa=
chter=E2=80=94the beau ideal of how auction house marketing is supposed to =
work. He advised them in putting together their collection at a time when a=
uction houses specialists still played that
role, traveling with them to Rome and Montreal to view pictures, sometimes =
accompanied by their interior designer, Ina Lindemann, whom Wachter would l=
ater hire to decorate his own home. He brokered the Saunders=E2=80=99 priva=
te purchase of eight exceptional Old Masters works from the Hornsteins, inc=
luding the Dou, Lawrence, and Mel=C3=A9ndez.

=C2=A0

It was also Wachter who steered them to a landscape painting
by Frans Post that had been discovered in a barn in Connecticut. The painti=
ng, which they found out had belonged to Louis XIV, was filthy. But the Sau=
nderses paid $2.2 million for it on Wachter=E2=80=99s advice and sent it to=
 a conservator, who started by cleaning a small square of the sky, uncoveri=
ng a brilliant blue, at which point the couple knew they had a masterpiece.=
 Wachter advised them to copy an elaborate frame from the Rijksmuseum, whic=
h took a Dutch artisan a
year to replicate. The painting, in that frame, is now being offered at Sot=
heby=E2=80=99s at an estimate of $6 million. (The artist=E2=80=99s current =
record, set in 1997, is $4.5 million.)

The auction also includes a pair of Guardi paintings that the couple acquir=
ed at Sotheby=E2=80=99s in 2000 for $5.6 million and are now being offered =
for $10 million. (In that same auction they underbid Rubens=E2=80=99s Portr=
ait of a Man as Mars, which would eventually end up in the Fisch Davidson
collection.) Their primary competitor for the Guardis happened to be at lun=
ch and unreachable when the lot came up at auction, so they got the paintin=
g for far less than they might have otherwise.

The Saunders collection on view at the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts. Photo:=
 Sandra
Sellars

Thomas Saunders, who died in 2022, was a managing director and chairman at
Morgan Stanley for two decades=E2=80=94where he structured I.P.O.s for comp=
anies like Apple and GE, and did the underwriting for Margaret Thatcher=E2=
=80=99s telecom privatization=E2=80=94before going on to co-found his own p=
rivate equity firm. He also served as chairman of the Heritage Foundation, =
which of course famously authored Project 2025. The couple were active phil=
anthropists, with much of their largesse going to Virginia institutions suc=
h as UVA, the Virginia Military Institute, and the Thomas
Jefferson Foundation.

=C2=A0

Jordan first tested the auction waters by offering English and European fur=
niture, silver, ceramics, and Chinese export porcelain in a single-owner sa=
le at Sotheby=E2=80=99s in February 2024, including items she=E2=80=99d pur=
chased in the Duke and Duchess of Windsor sale there in 1998. The sale of 3=
16 objects made $3.3 million, against an estimate of $2 million.

=C2=A0

Additional highlights in the upcoming sale include a de Heem large-scale fl=
oral still life at an estimate of $8 million, higher than the artist=E2=80=
=99s current auction record of $7.6 million. Mel=C3=A9ndez=E2=80=99s Still =
Life with a Cauliflower is estimated at $5 million, and Lawrence=E2=80=99s =
Portrait of Miss Julia Peel is estimated at $6 million. It is the best exam=
ple by the artist to appear at auction in nearly two decades, when the auct=
ion
record of $4 million was set. A rare pair of Hals portraits is on offer for=
 $6 million, and a genre scene by Dou, a student of Rembrandt, is estimated=
 at $5 million. Thomas recalled seeing the Dou painting on view in a 2001 t=
raveling exhibition of the artist=E2=80=99s works: =E2=80=9CWhat can I say =
about my feelings as I looked at our Dou hanging in the National Gallery in=
 Washington next to Queen Elizabeth II=E2=80=99s Dou? God bless America!=E2=
=80=9D

=C2=A0

After London, the paintings are touring to Amsterdam and Brussels during TE=
FAF Maastricht, then Los Angeles and Hong Kong in April. As Jordan would te=
ll the next generation of collectors, =E2=80=9CLong live the hunt!=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8A

