n-bottom:0px;">The couple=E2=80=99s collection spans the 16th to 19th centu=
ries, and represents some
of the greatest artists of that era, ranging from still lifes by <strong>Ja=
n Davidsz. </strong><strong>de Heem</strong> and <strong>Luis Mel=C3=A9ndez=
</strong> to portraits by <strong>Frans Hals</strong> and <strong>Thomas La=
wrence</strong> to <em>vedute</em> by <strong>Canaletto</strong> and <stron=
g>Francesco Guardi</strong>, as well as works by <strong>Gerrit Dou</strong=
> and <strong>Peter Paul Rubens</strong>. The auction comprises 56 works, w=
ith 42 being offered in a dedicated single-owner sale
and the rest in the various-owners sale the following day. By comparison, S=
otheby=E2=80=99s most valuable collection of Old Masters sold to date was t=
he Fisch Davidson collection, which made $76 million in 2023=E2=80=94it was=
 only 12 pictures, all Italian Baroque, with two-thirds of the value coming=
 from just two Rubens paintings.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>This =
will be the first time in decades that the Saunders paintings are coming on=
 the market, since the couple bought many of them via private
transactions between 1998 and 2002. =E2=80=9CThe Saunderses wanted beautifu=
l pictures in wonderful condition,=E2=80=9D said Wachter, who worked closel=
y with the couple to assemble the collection that would fill their triplex =
penthouse at 812 Park Avenue. =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s amazing is how I mana=
ged to find all these things at that time. Not sure I could do it in the sa=
me way today,=E2=80=9D he told me, in part because Old Masters collections =
like those of <strong>Renata</strong> and <strong>Michal Hornstein</strong>=
,
<strong>Rose-Marie</strong> and <strong>Eijk van Otterloo</strong>, and <st=
rong>Susan</strong> and <strong>Matthew Weatherbie</strong> have been donat=
ed to museums.</p></div>
