><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">The Saunders=E2=80=99 collecting journey is ending right whe=
re it started. In January
1998, Sotheby=E2=80=99s client services executive <strong>Mish Tworkowski</=
strong> invited Jordan to lunch at the auction house, where they wandered d=
own to the Old Masters exhibition and happened upon the painting <em>View o=
f the Isola della Giudecca</em>, by Guardi. Tworkowski introduced her to Wa=
chter, who spoke eloquently about the composition. The Saunderses went on t=
o purchase the Guardi at auction for $1.3 million. (It=E2=80=99s being offe=
red in May at an estimate of $4 million.) In the same sale, they
underbid a portrait by <strong>Johannes Cornelisz Verspronck</strong> that =
ended up being bought by the National Gallery for $1.65 million.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">Thus began their four-year buying spree and decades-long friendsh=
ip with Wachter=E2=80=94the <em>beau ideal </em>of how auction house market=
ing is supposed to work. He advised them in putting together their collecti=
on at a time when auction houses specialists still played that
role, traveling with them to Rome and Montreal to view pictures, sometimes =
accompanied by their interior designer, <strong>Ina Lindemann</strong>, who=
m Wachter would later hire to decorate his own home. He brokered the Saunde=
rs=E2=80=99 private purchase of eight exceptional Old Masters works from th=
e Hornsteins, including the Dou, Lawrence, and Mel=C3=A9ndez.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">It was also Wachter who steered them to a landscape painting
by <strong>Frans Post </strong>that had been discovered in a barn in Connec=
ticut. The painting, which they found out had belonged to <strong>Louis XIV=
</strong>, was filthy. But the Saunderses paid $2.2 million for it on Wacht=
er=E2=80=99s advice and sent it to a conservator, who started by cleaning a=
 small square of the sky, uncovering a brilliant blue, at which point the c=
ouple knew they had a masterpiece. Wachter advised them to copy an elaborat=
e frame from the Rijksmuseum, which took a Dutch artisan a
year to replicate. The painting, in that frame, is now being offered at Sot=
heby=E2=80=99s at an estimate of $6 million. (The artist=E2=80=99s current =
record, set in 1997, is $4.5 million.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>The a=
uction also includes a pair of Guardi paintings that the couple acquired at=
 Sotheby=E2=80=99s in 2000 for $5.6 million and are now being offered for $=
10 million. (In that same auction they underbid Rubens=E2=80=99s <em>Portra=
it of a Man as Mars</em>, which would eventually end up in the Fisch Davids=
on
collection.) Their primary competitor for the Guardis happened to be at lun=
